CodeList.Name: Cardiovascular Test Code

Description.TranslatedText: A terminology codelist to describe the test code for a physiological examination of the cardiovascular system.

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The augmentation pressure divided by the aortic pulse pressure (aortic systolic minus aortic diastolic pressure) multiplied by 100, expressed as a percentage.
The aortic augmentation index normalized to a heart rate of 75 beats per minute.

The difference between the second pressure peak in the aortic wave, secondary to the pressure wave reflection from the sites of peripheral arterial impedance mismatch (P2) and the first pressure peak in the aortic wave form, secondary to ventricular ejection (P1).
The first pressure peak in the aortic wave form secondary to ventricular ejection.
The second pressure peak in the aortic waveform secondary to pressure wave reflection from the periphery.
The peak velocity of the annular motion during late ventricular diastole (the active filling of the ventricle).
The peak velocity of the annular motion during early ventricular diastole (the passive filling of the ventricle).
The 2-dimensional surface enclosed within a boundary of a cardiovascular structure and measured at end ventricular diastole.
The 2-dimensional surface enclosed within a boundary of a cardiovascular structure and measured at end ventricular systole.

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Aortic Regur Jet Width LVOT Diam Rt
Aortic Regurgitant Jet Width to Left Ventricular Outflow Tract Diameter Ratio
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio) of the aortic regurgitant jet width to left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) diameter.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Aortic Regurgitant Jet Width to Left Ventricular Outflow Tract Diameter Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the aortic valve expressed as a percentage of the anterograde flow volume.
The measured width of the regurgitant jet of blood into the left ventricular outflow tract.
A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the aortic valve.
The area of the vena contracta of the aortic valve.
The width of the vena contracta of the aortic valve.
The volume of blood per unit time passing through a specified location, such as a point in a blood vessel or an entire organ.

An indication as to whether there is a new acute reduction in coronary flow (TIMI grade 0-1) in the absence of dissection, thrombus, spasm, or high-grade residual stenosis at the original PCI lesion site.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Coronary No Reflow at PCI Site Indicator

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The measure of an individual's cardiac output divided by the individual's body surface area (CI= CO/BSA).
The total volume of blood pumped by the heart over a set period of time, conventionally one minute; it is calculated as heart rate times stroke volume (CO= HR x SV).
The pattern of the epicardial vessels supplying the posterolateral and posterior descending coronary arteries.
The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured at end ventricular diastole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Diastole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured at end ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Systole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured at mid ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Cross-sectional Diameter at Mid Ventricular Systole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: An indication as to whether there is doming of a cardiac valve cusp.
The assessment of the severity of doming of a cardiac valve cusp.
An indication as to whether there is a flailing cardiac valve cusp.
The assessment of the severity of a flailing cardiac valve cusp.
The time point during the cardiac cycle when the flail of one or more cardiac valve cusps occurs.
An indication as to whether there is a prolapsing cardiac valve cusp.
The assessment of the severity of a prolapsing cardiac valve cusp.
The time point during the cardiac cycle when the prolapse of one or more cardiac valve cusps occurs.
An indication as to whether there is restricted motion of a cardiac valve cusp.
The assessment of the severity of restricted motion of a cardiac valve cusp.
An indication as to whether there is tethering of a cardiac valve cusp.
The assessment of the severity of tethering of a cardiac valve cusp.
An indication as to whether there is a thickened cardiac valve cusp.
The assessment of the severity of a thickening cardiac cusp.
An indication as to whether there is prolapsing of a cardiac valve chordae tendinae.
The qualitative measurement of the severity of cardiac valvular regurgitation.
The qualitative measurement of the severity of cardiac valvular stenosis.
The trajectory of the retrograde blood flow from a cardiac valve.
The assessment of the movement of the cardiac muscle, either as a whole or at one or more specific anatomical locations.
The extent downward or inward; the perpendicular measurement from the surface downward to determine deepness. (NCI)
A measurement of the effective regurgitant orifice area of the valve.
The magnitude of the ejection wave that occurs when blood is ejected into the aorta by the left ventricle.
An indication as to whether there is re-narrowing of a stent implanted at a lesion site to treat a prior stenosis, to a diameter stenosis of greater than 50% within the stent.

An act or process of elucidation; explication, or explanation of the meaning of the event or thing via the assignment of objects from the domain to the constants of a formal language, truth-values to the proposition symbols, truth-functions to the connectives, other functions to the function symbols, and extensions to the predicates, if any. The assignments are result of human logic application and are not native to the symbols of the formal language.
The percentage of myocardial tissue which exhibits characteristics of inadequate blood flow (ischemia).

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Inferior Vena Cava Collapse Sniff Ind
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: An indication as to whether inferior vena cava collapse occurred with sniff.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Inferior Vena Cava Collapse Due to Sniff Test Indicator

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The diameter across the left atrium measured at the end of systole.

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Largest Cross-sectional Diameter, End Ventricular Diastole
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The largest cross sectional diameter of a vascular structure measured at end ventricular diastole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Largest Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Diastole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The linear extent in space from one end of something to the other end, or the extent of something from beginning to end. (NCI)
The assessment of the largest cross-sectional thickness of a tissue.
The difference between the mean minimum lumen diameter (MLD) assessed immediately after an index procedure and the MLD assessed at follow-up angiography.
An indication as to whether there is re-narrowing of a lesion site following treatment of a prior stenosis, to a diameter stenosis of greater than 50% at the previously treated lesion site.
The diameter across the ventricle at the end of diastole, excluding the thickness of the walls.
The diameter across the ventricle at the end of systole, excluding the thickness of the walls.

The percent or fraction of the left ventricular end diastolic volume ejected in systole. The left ventricular ejection fraction is equal to the left ventricular stroke volume divided by the left ventricular end diastolic volume.

The reduction in the length of the end-diastolic diameter dimension that occurs between end-systole and end-diastole, expressed as a fraction of the end-diastolic dimension. Calculation of the left ventricular fractional shortening is per the following formula: [(end-diastolic dimension minus end-systolic dimension) divided by end-diastolic dimension] multiplied by 100.

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Left Ventricular Outflow Tract Peak Velocity
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A measurement of the maximum velocity of blood flow measured in the left ventricular outflow tract during left ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Left Ventricular Outflow Tract Peak Velocity

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Left Ventricular Outflow Tract Velocity Time Integral
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The integral of all of the instantaneous flow velocities within the left ventricular outflow tract during left ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Left Ventricular Outflow Tract Velocity Time Integral

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The estimated average of atrial pressure.
The amount of matter in an object.
A measurement of the mean velocity of blood across an area or tissue.
The mean of the inside diameters of the normal blood vessel segments.
The minimum diameter of the inside of a blood vessel (lumen) derived quantitatively in a single view.
The ratio of the peak early ventricular diastolic (E) transmitral velocity to the peak late ventricular diastolic (A) transmitral velocity.
The ratio of the peak early ventricular diastolic (E) transmitral velocity to the peak early mitral annular motion velocity (e').

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Major Axis Cross-sectional Diameter, End Ventricular Diastole
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured along the major axis at end ventricular diastole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Major Axis Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Diastole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Major Axis Cross-sectional Diameter, End Ventricular Systole
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured along the major axis at end ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Major Axis Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Systole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Minor Axis Cross-sectional Diameter, End Ventricular Diastole
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured along the minor axis at end ventricular diastole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Minor Axis Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Diastole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Minor Axis Cross-sectional Diameter, End Ventricular Systole
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross sectional diameter of a cardiovascular structure measured along the minor axis at end ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Minor Axis Cross-sectional Diameter at End Ventricular Systole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Mitral Regur Jet Area L Atrial Area Rt
Mitral Regurgitant Jet Area to Left Atrial Area Ratio
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio) of the mitral regurgitant jet area to left atrial area.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Mitral Regurgitant Jet Area to Left Atrial Area Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the mitral valve expressed as a percentage of the anterograde flow volume.
The measured area of the regurgitant jet of blood into the left atrium.
A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the mitral valve.
The area of the vena contracta of the mitral valve.
The width of the vena contracta of the mitral valve.
Number of major epicardial vessels with greater than or equal to 70% reduction in diameter or greater than or equal to 50% reduction in cross-sectional area.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Number of Diseased Coronary Artery Vessels

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A measurement of the maximum velocity of blood across an area or tissue.
The value calculated as 100 x (1 - MLD/RVD), using the mean quantitative values for minimum lumen diameter (MLD) and reference vessel diameter (RVD).
The peak velocity of blood flow across a cardiac valve during late ventricular diastole (the active filling of the ventricle).
The peak velocity of blood flow across a cardiac valve during early ventricular diastole (the passive filling of the ventricle).

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Pulmonic Regur Jet Width RVOT Diam Rt
Pulmonic Regurgitant Jet Width to Right Ventricular Outflow Tract Diameter Ratio
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio) of the pulmonic regurgitant jet width to right ventricular outflow tract (RVOT) diameter.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Pulmonic Regurgitant Jet Width to Right Ventricular Outflow Tract Diameter Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The determination of whether blood flow in the pulmonary veins is greater during ventricular systole or diastole.
The resistance to blood flow through the pulmonary vasculature.
A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the pulmonic valve expressed as a percentage of the anterograde flow volume.
The measured width of the regurgitant jet of blood into the right ventricular outflow tract.
A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the pulmonic valve.
The area of the vena contracta of the pulmonic valve.
The width of the vena contracta of the pulmonic valve.
The distance traveled by the peak of the ventricular ejection pressure wave per unit of time.
The reflected-to-forward pressure wave amplitude ratio. (Hashimoto J et al, J Hypertens. 2008 May;26(5):1017-24)
The summation of the numerous waves being reflected by sites of impedance mismatch where central elastic arteries join more muscular arteries.
An indication as to whether there is systolic anterior motion of a cardiac valve and its associated structures.
The assessment of the severity of the systolic anterior motion of a cardiac valve and its associated structures.
The difference in the volumes of blood between the points of maximum dilation and maximum contraction. This is the end diastolic volume minus the end systolic volume.
The resistance to blood flow through the systemic vasculature.
The cross-sectional thickness of a cardiovascular structure measured at end ventricular diastole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Cross-sectional Thickness at End Ventricular Diastole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The cross-sectional thickness of a cardiovascular structure measured at end ventricular systole.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Cross-sectional Thickness at End Ventricular Systole

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Tricus Regur Jet Area R Atrial Area Rt
Tricuspid Regurgitant Jet Area to Right Atrial Area Ratio
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio) of the tricuspid regurgitant jet area to the right atrial area.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Tricuspid Regurgitant Jet Area to Right Atrial Area Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the tricuspid valve expressed as a percentage of the anterograde flow volume.
The measured area of the regurgitant jet of blood into the right atrium.
A measurement of the volume of retrograde blood flow across the orifice of the tricuspid valve.
The area of the vena contracta of the tricuspid valve.
The width of the vena contracta of the tricuspid valve.
The integral of all of the forward flow velocities during the time of blood flow across or within a specified area.
The vertical force exerted by a mass as a result of gravity. (NCI)
The extent or measurement of something from side to side. (NCI)

CodeList.nciodm:PreferredTerm: CDISC SDTM Cardiovascular Test Code Terminology
